{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"339e28f7-0ec0-4084-9ee3-dcd858e29c0e","content":"This is a known breaking change. Android 15 (API 35) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering, which means `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` is ignored. In .NET MAUI 10, you need to react to **keyboard window insets** instead.\n\n**The fix:** In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, listen for IME insets and adjust the view's bottom padding:\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        if (Window?.DecorView is { } decorView)\n        {\n            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(decorView,\n                new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n        }\n    }\n\n    private class KeyboardInsetsListener\n        : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n            int bottom = Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom);\n            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAlso ensure your `AndroidManifest.xml` still has:\n\n```xml\n<activity android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\" ... />\n```\n\n**Why this works:** Instead of the deprecated resize mode, `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` reports the keyboard's exact height. The listener pushes the bottom padding up by that amount, keeping your input bar visible. When the keyboard closes, `ime.Bottom` returns to `0` and the system bar inset takes over.\n\nYou can remove the old `UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust` call — it's now a no-op on API 35+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5208595f-88d1-4704-a6e1-9eabbdeee977","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10.\n\nThis is a known change in .NET MAUI. In .NET 10 (which targets Android 15+ / API 35), edge-to-edge display is enforced by default, and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated in Android API 30 and removed/ignored in Android 15.\n\nThe solution in .NET 10 is to use the new keyboard insets handling. Let me provide a clear answer.\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI 10, Android 15's edge-to-edge enforcement makes the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` approach obsolete, so I need to explain the new insets-based approach that handles keyboard visibility properly. The deprecated API was replaced by `WindowInsetsCompat` for handling keyboard insets in modern Android. For .NET MAUI 10 on Android 15+, the framework now handles edge-to-edge automatically, so you can rely on the built-in keyboard inset support rather than the old `UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust` method, though you may still need `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` in the manifest for the windowing system itself. Setting up a window insets listener in the Android MainActivity to detect keyboard insets and adjust layout padding accordingly is the most reliable approach for MAUI 10. Actually, MAUI 10 has built-in support for this if edge-to-edge is configured properly, but since that's not working for the user, the manual insets listener approach is the way to go.","outputTokens":1985,"requestId":"B7D5:3EA14:183409:1FA67E:69FFDA8E"},"id":"09a5f3d6-2dae-428d-a4c1-0359c9167653","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:07.469Z","parentId":"aa6eb83f-d3f8-493b-822a-411e446a2a1c"}
